The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Business | Business Briefs
                                                                                                                           6                                                                                      Business Briefs
                              
	 Mumbai, Jan. 22: Sebi today asked some life insurance companies, including Bharti AXA and Bajaj Allianz Life Insurance, to explain why they did not seek its approval before offering ULIPs, which invest a portion of fund in stock markets. Section 12 (1B) of the Sebi Act prohibits all from offering investment schemes, including MFs, in securities markets, unless approved by Sebi.                            
	 New Delhi, Jan. 22: Core industries grew 6 per cent in December against a meagre 0.7 per cent a year back, suggesting that growth in industrial production is on a firm footing. Six key sectors  crude, petroleum refinery products, coal, electricity, cement and finished steel  grew 4.8 per cent in April-December 2009 against 3.2 per cent a year ago.                            
	 New Delhi, Jan. 22: Prime Minister Manmohan Singh has asked the labour ministry to set up a panel, which will include representatives of the ministries of finance and industry, to address the problem of job loss because of the global economic slowdown.                             
	 New Delhi, Jan. 22: India wants the US Securities Exchange Commission to keep the interest of the investors of Satyam, now Mahindra Satyam, in mind while taking an action in the over Rs 7,000-crore accounting fraud case.                            
	 New Delhi, Jan. 22: Tata Teleservices prepaid CDMA customers can now make long distance calls at Rs 2 for five minutes. The new plan will charge Re 1 for five-minute local calls and Rs 2 for long-distance ones of same duration.                             
	 Bhubaneswar, Jan. 22: Posco India has signed an agreement with Orissa Power Transmission Company. This is the first move towards the construction of its mega steel plant near Paradip.                                                                                                                          
